@startuml ConsistentHashing

title High-Level Design: Consistent Hashing

skinparam backgroundColor #FAFAFA
skinparam componentStyle rectangle

' ─── Hash Ring ───
note as ring
  **Hash Ring (Virtual Nodes)**

  The hash ring spans 0 → 2^32 - 1 (circular)

        0
        │
  270 ──┼── 90           Servers mapped to ring:
        │                • Server A @ positions 30, 150, 270
       180               • Server B @ positions 60, 180, 330
                         • Server C @ positions 90, 210, 30

  Keys are hashed to a position on the ring.
  Request is served by the FIRST server clockwise
  from the key's position.

  Virtual Nodes (vnodes):
  Each physical server maps to multiple positions
  (e.g. 150 vnodes each) for uniform distribution.
end note

' ─── Component View ───
component "Client /\nRequest Router" as client #DDEEFF

package "Cache / DB Cluster" {
    node "Server A\n(vnodes: 30,150,270)" as sa #D5E8D4
    node "Server B\n(vnodes: 60,180,330)" as sb #D5E8D4
    node "Server C\n(vnodes: 90,210,30)"  as sc #D5E8D4
}

component "Consistent Hash\nRouter Library" as chr #FFF2CC

client --> chr : hash(key) → ring position
chr --> sa : keys mapping to A's range
chr --> sb : keys mapping to B's range
chr --> sc : keys mapping to C's range

note right of chr
  **Adding a new server D:**
  Only keys between D's predecessor
  and D's position are remapped.
  ≈ 1/N of total keys (minimal disruption)

  **Removing a server:**
  Its keys move to the next server clockwise.
  Only that server's keys are affected.

  **Without consistent hashing:**
  Adding/removing a node remaps
  ALL keys → thundering herd on DB.
end note

note bottom of sa
  **Real-world uses:**
  • Amazon DynamoDB / Dynamo paper
  • Apache Cassandra (token ring)
  • Memcached client libraries
  • CDN edge server selection
  • Distributed load balancers
end note

@enduml

